{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502053"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:38:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:38:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1821"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1821","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1821"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.78,0.09,0.06,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1821"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43557"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1821","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1821"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1821"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28571"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"2149"},{"type":"tags","id":"2777"},{"type":"tags","id":"3975"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1789"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1943"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43557"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman is in the recovery room following an elective right total knee replacement (performed under general anaesthesia). Her current blood pressure is 180/100 mmHg, which has been confirmed on a manual reading three times. Her usual blood pressure is around 155/90 mmHg. Her regular medications includes perindopril and hydrochlorothiazide, which were continued peri-operatively. She denies headache, visual disturbance, chest pain, dizziness, palpitations, and dyspnoea. She reports throbbing pain in her right knee at present with a pain score of 7 out of 10. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her pulse rate is 80/min, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 100% on room air, and temperature 36.9\u00b0C. She is tender to palpation over the right knee incision. Her peripheral pulses are strong. The capillary refill is less than two seconds. An indwelling catheter is in situ and is draining clear urine. A bedside electrocardiogram shows sinus rhythm with no acute changes. Her pre-operative blood tests are within the normal range.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["GTN patch","Analgesia","Calcium channel blocker","Beta blocker","Intravenous fluids"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMarked elevation in blood pressure in the post-operative period requires urgent assessment and management with intravenous antihypertensive therapy if appropriate. In this case the aetiology of the patient\u2019s hypertension is likely post-operative pain and therefore, adequate \u003Cstrong\u003Eanalgesia\u003C/strong\u003E will likely reduce the patients blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf hypertension is refractory to analgesia, other remedial causes should be ruled out and the hypertension addressed pharmacologically. The use of a \u003Cstrong\u003Ebeta-blocker \u003C/strong\u003Eor\u003Cstrong\u003E calcium channel blocker\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if pain was adequately controlled.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is nothing in this clinical scenario to suggest that the patient\u0027s problem is cardiac in origin, so there is no place for a \u003Cstrong\u003EGTN patch\u003C/strong\u003E. Whilst she will almost certainly have an intravenous access line in position, she does not need any additional \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous fluids\u003C/strong\u003E at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Inadequate analgesia is a common explanation for post-operative hypertension."],"references":["Varon J, Marik PE. Perioperative hypertension management. Vascular Health and Risk Management 2008; 4:615\u201327"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28571"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1821"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28571"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-22T17:26:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-03-22T17:26:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1821"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43557"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"